1) IMPORT & PREPARE DATA

Set working directory
#set working directory
#setwd()
Load data
#load Niphargus trait data
trait_data <- read_excel("Niphargus_morpho_data.xlsx", 
    col_types = c("text", "text", "numeric", "numeric", "numeric", 
        "numeric", "numeric", "numeric", 
        "numeric", "numeric", "numeric", 
        "numeric", "numeric", "numeric", 
        "numeric", "numeric", "numeric"), na = "NA")
#check
head(trait_data)
## # A tibble: 6 x 17
##   species       ecology body_length pV_length pVI_length pVII_length cxII_length
##   <chr>         <chr>         <dbl>     <dbl>      <dbl>       <dbl>       <dbl>
## 1 N_aggtelekie~ <NA>           7.25      2.04       2.91        3.09       0.41 
## 2 N_aulicus     <NA>           9.22      3.52       4.53        4.64       0.945
## 3 N_bihorensis~ <NA>          12.4       3.72       4.23        5.28       0.735
## 4 N_bihorensis~ <NA>          11.4       3.37       4.93        5.35       0.73 
## 5 N_boskovici   <NA>           9.66      2.78       3.78        4.05       0.625
## 6 N_brachytels~ <NA>          16.7       3.98       5.42        5.79       1.01 
## # ... with 10 more variables: cxIII_length <dbl>, pVb_width <dbl>,
## #   pVIb_width <dbl>, pVIIb_width <dbl>, gnI_l <dbl>, gnI_w <dbl>, gnI_d <dbl>,
## #   gnII_l <dbl>, gnII_w <dbl>, gnII_d <dbl>
#load Niphargus phylogenetic tree
tree <- read.nexus(file = "consensus_tree.nex")
Mutate and filter data
#compute gnathopod perimeters from three gnathopod measures (sum of gnathopod length, width and diagonal)
trait_data <- trait_data %>% rowwise() %>% mutate(gnI_perim = sum(gnI_l, gnI_w, gnI_d))
trait_data <- trait_data %>% rowwise() %>% mutate(gnII_perim = sum(gnII_l, gnII_w, gnII_d))
#remove excess columns
trait_data <- trait_data[,-c(12:17)]
#remove species with missing morphological data
#N gallicus, N patrizii, N virei C
trait_data <- trait_data %>% drop_na(c(4:13))
#remove problematic species
#N montellianus H affects interstitial species models as it is morphologically very different from others
trait_data <- trait_data %>% filter(species != "N_montellianus_H")
Create three data subsets according to Niphargus ecology
#subset trait dataset to contain interstitial species
interstitial <- trait_data %>% filter(ecology == "interstitial")
#subset trait dataset to contain cave lake species
cave_lake <- trait_data %>% filter(ecology == "cave lake")
#subset trait dataset to contain cave stream species
cave_stream <- trait_data %>% filter(ecology == "stream")
Create three pruned phylogenetic trees
#create vectors with species names
interstitial_sp <- as.vector(interstitial$species)
cave_lake_sp <- as.vector(cave_lake$species)
cave_stream_sp <- as.vector(cave_stream$species)

#prune trees
tree_int <- keep.tip(phy = tree, tip = interstitial_sp)
tree_cave_lake <- keep.tip(phy = tree, tip = cave_lake_sp)
tree_cave_stream <- keep.tip(phy = tree, tip = cave_stream_sp)

#assign rownames
interstitial <- data.frame(interstitial, row.names = 1)
cave_lake <- data.frame(cave_lake, row.names = 1)
cave_stream <- data.frame(cave_stream, row.names = 1)
#remove excess objects
rm(cave_lake_sp, cave_stream_sp, interstitial_sp)

2) DATA ANALYSIS 1: PHYLOGENETIC REGRESSIONS

2.1) Interstitial species

#iterate phylogenetic regression function through columns - interstitial species
phylolm_int <- lapply(interstitial[,-c(1:2)], function(y){
  
        phylolm(formula = y ~ interstitial$body_length, 
                data = interstitial, phy = tree_int, 
                model = "BM", track = FALSE)
  
})

#extract residuals from lists
int_res <- lapply(phylolm_int, function (x) x[c("residuals")])

#convert to dataframe and assign original column names
int_res_df <- as.data.frame(int_res)
colnames(int_res_df) <- names(int_res)
#add back scaled body length column
body_length <- scale(interstitial$body_length)
int_res_df <- cbind(int_res_df, body_length)

#remove excess objects
rm(phylolm_int, int_res)

2.2) Cave lake species

#iterate phylogenetic regression function through columns - cave lake species
phylolm_lake <- lapply(cave_lake[,-c(1:2)], function(y){
  
        phylolm(formula = y ~ cave_lake$body_length, 
                data = cave_lake, phy = tree_cave_lake, 
                model = "BM", track = FALSE)
  
})

#extract residuals from lists
lake_res <- lapply(phylolm_lake, function (x) x[c("residuals")])

#convert to dataframe and assign original column names
lake_res_df <- as.data.frame(lake_res)
colnames(lake_res_df) <- names(lake_res)
#add back scaled body length column
body_length <- scale(cave_lake$body_length)
lake_res_df <- cbind(lake_res_df, body_length)

#remove excess objects
rm(phylolm_lake, lake_res)

2.3) Cave stream species

#iterate phylogenetic regression function through columns - cave stream species
phylolm_stream <- lapply(cave_stream[,-c(1:2)], function(y){
  
        phylolm(formula = y ~ cave_stream$body_length, 
                data = cave_stream, phy = tree_cave_stream, 
                model = "BM", track = FALSE)
  
})

#extract residuals from lists
stream_res <- lapply(phylolm_stream, function (x) x[c("residuals")])

#convert to dataframe and assign original column names
stream_res_df <- as.data.frame(stream_res)
colnames(stream_res_df) <- names(stream_res)
#add back scaled body length column
body_length <- scale(cave_stream$body_length)
stream_res_df <- cbind(stream_res_df, body_length)

#remove excess objects
rm(phylolm_stream, stream_res, body_length)

3) DATA ANALYSIS 2: PHYLOGENETIC PCA

We divided morphological traits in three groups; “body shape” includes coxae II and III lengths and pereopod V-VII basis widths; “locomotion” includes pereopod V-VII lengths and body length, and “trophic position” includes gnathopod I and II perimeters.

3.1) Interstitial species

#create data matrices for each set of traits (traits in columns)
int_shape <- as.matrix(int_res_df[,c(4:8)]) #body shape
int_locom <- as.matrix(int_res_df[,c(1:3, 11)]) #locomotion
int_tp <- as.matrix(int_res_df[,c(9,10)]) #trophic position

#run PCAs
int_shape_pca <- phyl.pca(tree = tree_int, int_shape, method = "BM", mode = "cov")
int_locom_pca <- phyl.pca(tree = tree_int, int_locom, method = "BM", mode = "cov")
int_tp_pca <- phyl.pca(tree = tree_int, int_tp, method = "BM", mode = "cov")
“Body shape” PCA results

7) DATA ANALYSIS 5: COMPUTE FUNCTIONAL DIVERSITY AMONG THREE ECOLOGICAL GROUPS

7.1) PREPARE DATA AND AGAIN RUN PHYLOGENETIC REGRESSION AND PHYLOGENETIC PCAs

In this analysis, species are not divided into ecological groups prior to phylogenetic regressions.

Edit data, run phylogenetic regression

#remove epikarst species (ecology = NA)
trait_data <- trait_data %>% drop_na(c(2))
#create vector with species names
species <- as.vector(trait_data$species)
#prune tree
tree <- keep.tip(phy = tree, tip = species)
#assign rownames
species_data <- data.frame(trait_data, row.names = 1)

#iterate phylogenetic regression function through columns 
phylolm <- lapply(species_data[,-c(1:2)], function(y){
  
        phylolm(formula = y ~ species_data$body_length, 
                data = species_data, phy = tree, 
                model = "BM", track = FALSE)
  
})

#extract residuals from lists
residuals <- lapply(phylolm, function (x) x[c("residuals")])

#convert to dataframe and assign original column names
residuals_df <- as.data.frame(residuals)
colnames(residuals_df) <- names(residuals)
#add back scaled body length column
body_length <- scale(species_data$body_length)
residuals_df <- cbind(residuals_df, body_length)

#remove excess objects
rm(residuals, phylolm, species_data)

Run phylogenetic PCAs

#create data matrices for phylogenetic PCA (traits in columns)
shape <- as.matrix(residuals_df[,c(4:8)]) #Body shape
locom <- as.matrix(residuals_df[,c(1:3, 11)]) #Locomotion
tp <- as.matrix(residuals_df[,c(9,10)]) #Trophic position

#run PCAs
shape_pca <- phyl.pca(tree = tree, shape, method = "BM", mode = "cov") #PC1 explains 72% of variance
locom_pca <- phyl.pca(tree = tree, locom, method = "BM", mode = "cov") #PC1 explains 81% of variance
tp_pca <- phyl.pca(tree = tree, tp, method = "BM", mode = "cov") #PC1 explains 94% of variance

#save PC1 scores
species_traits_df <- as.data.frame(cbind(locom_pca$S[,1], shape_pca$S[,1], tp_pca$S[,1]))
colnames(species_traits_df) <- c("PC1_locom", "PC1_shape", "PC1_tp")

Create ecology dataframe

#create dataframe with ecology information
ecology <- data.frame(trait_data[,c(1,2)], row.names = 1)
